Human papillomavirus infection: epidemiology and pathophysiology. More than 120 different types of the human papillomavirus (HPV) have been isolated >40 of these types infect the epithelial lining of the anogenital tract and other mucosal areas. In the majority of individuals, HPV infections are transient and asymptomatic with most new infections resolving within 2 years. Epidemiological data from the U.S. National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey determined that the prevalence of HPV infection in a representative sample of women was highest in those aged 20-24 years (44.8%). HPV infection has been firmly established as the primary cause of cervical cancer. It is not clearly understood why HPV infections resolve in certain individuals and result in cervical intraepithelial neoplasias in others, but several factors are thought to play a role